# AGENTS.md

This directory is linked to an [AgentClash](https://agentclash.dev) workspace. Use this playbook when an AI coding agent (Claude Code, Cursor, Codex, etc.) needs to race models on this project's challenge packs.

- **Workspace:** raj-personal (`00000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001`)
- **Deployments available:** `claude-4.7`, `gemini-3`, `gpt-5`

## The two-command recipe

Given a challenge pack at `./<name>.yaml`, race it against one or more deployed models:

```bash
# 1. Sanity-check the pack (fails fast on bad YAML):
agentclash challenge-pack check ./<name>.yaml --json

# 2. Race and get a structured scorecard:
agentclash eval ./<name>.yaml \
  --models <m1>,<m2>,... \
  --json --non-interactive
```

Exit codes:

- `0` pass — all deployed agents completed and no regression vs baseline.
- `1` fail / regression — run failed, an agent didn't complete (unless `--allow-partial`), or an agent regressed vs baseline. `baseline.regressions[]` in the JSON output lists the affected agents.
- `2` timeout — the run didn't reach a terminal status before `--timeout` elapsed.

## Baselines (regression verdict)

`eval` auto-manages a baseline named `main` per workspace:

- First eval in a workspace saves the run as `main`.
- Every subsequent eval compares against `main` and fails fast if any agent that passed in the baseline didn't pass this time.

Additional flags for fine-grained control:

- `--compare-to <name>` — diff against a non-default baseline.
- `--save-as <name>` — bookmark this run under a different name (baseline `main` stays untouched unless this is the first run).
- `--no-baseline` — skip both save and compare entirely (useful when iterating on pack content).

When an explicit `--compare-to <name>` misses, eval fails fast before running — no surprise scorecards against missing bookmarks.

## Error codes to branch on

Instead of parsing English, match on `error.code` in the JSON error envelope:

| Code | Meaning | Agent action |
|------|---------|--------------|
| `MODEL_NOT_FOUND` | The name didn't resolve in the model catalog. | Ask the human for a valid model name. |
| `MODEL_AMBIGUOUS` | The name matched >1 catalog entry. `details.candidates` lists them. | Pick one from the list or ask the human. |
| `DEPLOYMENT_NOT_FOUND` | Model resolves, but isn't deployed in this workspace. `details.deploy_url` points to the web UI. | Tell the human to deploy at the link. Do **not** try to provision — that needs provider API keys you should not touch. |
| `REGRESSION_DETECTED` | New scorecard regressed vs baseline. `details.regressions` lists (task, model) pairs. | Summarize the regressions to the human. |
| `PARTIAL_EXECUTION` | At least one `run_agent` failed (rate limit, auth). | Default is to exit 1; pass `--allow-partial` if that's acceptable for this run. |
| `MISSING_FLAG` | Non-interactive run missing a required flag. `field` names it. | Supply the named flag and retry. |

## Scaffolding a new challenge pack

```bash
agentclash challenge-pack new <name>
# Writes ./<name>.yaml with a commented starter challenge.
```

The pack YAML has a `challenges:` array. Each entry is `{key, title, challenge_input, expected_output, ...}`. See `docs/challenge-packs` on the web for the full schema.

## When the human wants a new model

New providers and deployments live in the web app. The CLI does **not** enter provider API keys — that's deliberately kept in the browser flow, which has full SSO/credentialed UX. If a needed model isn't listed above, tell the human:

> Deploy it at https://agentclash.dev/workspaces/00000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001/deployments, then run `agentclash link` here to refresh this file.

(Advanced CLI-first users can also run `agentclash init --provision --provider <p> --model <m>`, but that requires provider keys to be accessible to the current shell.)

